msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:30
msgid "Tests were collected and run but some of the tests failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:31
msgid "Test execution was interrupted by the user"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:32
msgid "Internal error happened while executing tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:33
msgid "pytest command line usage error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:0
msgid "Exit code 5"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:34
msgid "No tests were collected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:36
msgid ""
"They are represented by the :class:`_pytest.config.ExitCode` enum. The exit "
"codes being a part of the public API can be imported and accessed directly "
"using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:38
msgid "from pytest import ExitCode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:44
msgid ""
"If you would like to customize the exit code in some scenarios, specially "
"when no tests are collected, consider using the `pytest-custom_exit_code "
"<https://github.com/yashtodi94/pytest-custom_exit_code>`__ plugin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:51
msgid "Getting help on version, option names, environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:53
msgid ""
"pytest --version   # shows where pytest was imported from\n"
"pytest --fixtures  # show available builtin function arguments\n"
"pytest -h | --help # show help on command line and config file options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:63
msgid "Stopping after the first (or N) failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:65
msgid "To stop the testing process after the first (N) failures:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:67
msgid ""
"pytest -x           # stop after first failure\n"
"pytest --maxfail=2  # stop after two failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:75
msgid "Specifying tests / selecting tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:77
msgid ""
"Pytest supports several ways to run and select tests from the command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:79
msgid "**Run tests in a module**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:81
msgid "pytest test_mod.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:85
msgid "**Run tests in a directory**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:87
msgid "pytest testing/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:91
msgid "**Run tests by keyword expressions**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:93
msgid "pytest -k \"MyClass and not method\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:97
msgid ""
"This will run tests which contain names that match the given *string "
"expression* (case-insensitive), which can include Python operators that use "
"filenames, class names and function names as variables. The example above "
"will run ``TestMyClass.test_something``  but not ``TestMyClass."
"test_method_simple``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:103
msgid "**Run tests by node ids**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:105
msgid ""
"Each collected test is assigned a unique ``nodeid`` which consist of the "
"module filename followed by specifiers like class names, function names and "
"parameters from parametrization, separated by ``::`` characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:108
msgid "To run a specific test within a module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:110
msgid "pytest test_mod.py::test_func"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:115
msgid "Another example specifying a test method in the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:117
msgid "pytest test_mod.py::TestClass::test_method"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:121
msgid "**Run tests by marker expressions**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:123
msgid "pytest -m slow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:127
msgid ""
"Will run all tests which are decorated with the ``@pytest.mark.slow`` "
"decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:129
msgid "For more information see :ref:`marks <mark>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:131
msgid "**Run tests from packages**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:133
msgid "pytest --pyargs pkg.testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:137
msgid ""
"This will import ``pkg.testing`` and use its filesystem location to find and "
"run tests from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:141
msgid "Modifying Python traceback printing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:143
msgid "Examples for modifying traceback printing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:145
msgid ""
"pytest --showlocals # show local variables in tracebacks\n"
"pytest -l           # show local variables (shortcut)\n"
"\n"
"pytest --tb=auto    # (default) 'long' tracebacks for the first and last\n"
"                     # entry, but 'short' style for the other entries\n"
"pytest --tb=long    # exhaustive, informative traceback formatting\n"
"pytest --tb=short   # shorter traceback format\n"
"pytest --tb=line    # only one line per failure\n"
"pytest --tb=native  # Python standard library formatting\n"
"pytest --tb=no      # no traceback at all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:158
msgid ""
"The ``--full-trace`` causes very long traces to be printed on error (longer "
"than ``--tb=long``). It also ensures that a stack trace is printed on "
"**KeyboardInterrupt** (Ctrl+C). This is very useful if the tests are taking "
"too long and you interrupt them with Ctrl+C to find out where the tests are "
"*hanging*. By default no output will be shown (because KeyboardInterrupt is "
"caught by pytest). By using this option you make sure a trace is shown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:170
msgid "Detailed summary report"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:172
msgid ""
"The ``-r`` flag can be used to display a \"short test summary info\" at the "
"end of the test session, making it easy in large test suites to get a clear "
"picture of all failures, skips, xfails, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:175
msgid "It defaults to ``fE`` to list failures and errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:177
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:179
msgid ""
"# content of test_example.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def error_fixture():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_ok():\n"
"    print(\"ok\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_fail():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_error(error_fixture):\n"
"    pass\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_skip():\n"
"    pytest.skip(\"skipping this test\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_xfail():\n"
"    pytest.xfail(\"xfailing this test\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"always xfail\")\n"
"def test_xpass():\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:215
msgid ""
"$ pytest -ra\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py .FEsxX                                               [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"SKIPPED [1] $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/test_example.py:22: skipping this test\n"
"XFAIL test_example.py::test_xfail\n"
"  reason: xfailing this test\n"
"XPASS test_example.py::test_xpass always xfail\n"
"ERROR test_example.py::test_error - assert 0\n"
"FAILED test_example.py::test_fail - assert 0\n"
"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:252
msgid ""
"The ``-r`` options accepts a number of characters after it, with ``a`` used "
"above meaning \"all except passes\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:255
msgid "Here is the full list of available characters that can be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:257
msgid "``f`` - failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:258
msgid "``E`` - error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:259
msgid "``s`` - skipped"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:260
msgid "``x`` - xfailed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:261
msgid "``X`` - xpassed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:262
msgid "``p`` - passed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:263
msgid "``P`` - passed with output"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:265
msgid "Special characters for (de)selection of groups:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:267
msgid "``a`` - all except ``pP``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:268
msgid "``A`` - all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:269
msgid ""
"``N`` - none, this can be used to display nothing (since ``fE`` is the "
"default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:271
msgid ""
"More than one character can be used, so for example to only see failed and "
"skipped tests, you can execute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:273
msgid ""
"$ pytest -rfs\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 6 items\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py .FEsxX                                               [100%]\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_example.py::test_fail - assert 0\n"
"SKIPPED [1] $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/test_example.py:22: skipping this test\n"
"== 1 failed, 1 passed, 1 skipped, 1 xfailed, 1 xpassed, 1 error in 0.12s ==="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:306
msgid ""
"Using ``p`` lists the passing tests, whilst ``P`` adds an extra section "
"\"PASSES\" with those tests that passed but had captured output:"
