#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:348
msgid "Dropping to PDB_ (Python Debugger) on failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:352
msgid ""
"Python comes with a builtin Python debugger called PDB_.  ``pytest`` allows "
"one to drop into the PDB_ prompt via a command line option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:355
msgid "pytest --pdb"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:359
msgid ""
"This will invoke the Python debugger on every failure (or "
"KeyboardInterrupt). Often you might only want to do this for the first "
"failing test to understand a certain failure situation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:363
msgid ""
"pytest -x --pdb   # drop to PDB on first failure, then end test session\n"
"pytest --pdb --maxfail=3  # drop to PDB for first three failures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:368
msgid ""
"Note that on any failure the exception information is stored on ``sys."
"last_value``, ``sys.last_type`` and ``sys.last_traceback``. In interactive "
"use, this allows one to drop into postmortem debugging with any debug tool. "
"One can also manually access the exception information, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:374
msgid ""
">>> import sys\n"
">>> sys.last_traceback.tb_lineno\n"
"42\n"
">>> sys.last_value\n"
"AssertionError('assert result == \"ok\"',)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:383
msgid "Dropping to PDB_ (Python Debugger) at the start of a test"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:386
msgid ""
"``pytest`` allows one to drop into the PDB_ prompt immediately at the start "
"of each test via a command line option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:388
msgid "pytest --trace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:392
msgid "This will invoke the Python debugger at the start of every test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:397
msgid "Setting breakpoints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:401
msgid ""
"To set a breakpoint in your code use the native Python ``import pdb;pdb."
"set_trace()`` call in your code and pytest automatically disables its output "
"capture for that test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:404
msgid "Output capture in other tests is not affected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:405
msgid ""
"Any prior test output that has already been captured and will be processed "
"as such."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:407
msgid ""
"Output capture gets resumed when ending the debugger session (via the "
"``continue`` command)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:414
msgid "Using the builtin breakpoint function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:416
msgid ""
"Python 3.7 introduces a builtin ``breakpoint()`` function. Pytest supports "
"the use of ``breakpoint()`` with the following behaviours:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:419
msgid ""
"When ``breakpoint()`` is called and ``PYTHONBREAKPOINT`` is set to the "
"default value, pytest will use the custom internal PDB trace UI instead of "
"the system default ``Pdb``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:420
msgid ""
"When tests are complete, the system will default back to the system ``Pdb`` "
"trace UI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:421
msgid ""
"With ``--pdb`` passed to pytest, the custom internal Pdb trace UI is used "
"with both ``breakpoint()`` and failed tests/unhandled exceptions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:422
msgid "``--pdbcls`` can be used to specify a custom debugger class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:427
msgid "Profiling test execution duration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:430
msgid "To get a list of the slowest 10 test durations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:432
msgid "pytest --durations=10"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:436
msgid ""
"By default, pytest will not show test durations that are too small (<0.01s) "
"unless ``-vv`` is passed on the command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:442
msgid "Fault Handler"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:446
msgid ""
"The `faulthandler <https://docs.python.org/3/library/faulthandler.html>`__ "
"standard module can be used to dump Python tracebacks on a segfault or after "
"a timeout."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:449
msgid ""
"The module is automatically enabled for pytest runs, unless the ``-p no:"
"faulthandler`` is given on the command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:452
msgid ""
"Also the :confval:`faulthandler_timeout=X<faulthandler_timeout>` "
"configuration option can be used to dump the traceback of all threads if a "
"test takes longer than ``X`` seconds to finish (not available on Windows)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:458
msgid ""
"This functionality has been integrated from the external `pytest-"
"faulthandler <https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest-faulthandler>`__ plugin, "
"with two small differences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:462
msgid ""
"To disable it, use ``-p no:faulthandler`` instead of ``--no-faulthandler``: "
"the former can be used with any plugin, so it saves one option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:465
msgid ""
"The ``--faulthandler-timeout`` command-line option has become the :confval:"
"`faulthandler_timeout` configuration option. It can still be configured from "
"the command-line using ``-o faulthandler_timeout=X``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:471
msgid "Creating JUnitXML format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:473
msgid ""
"To create result files which can be read by Jenkins_ or other Continuous "
"integration servers, use this invocation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:476
msgid "pytest --junitxml=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:480
msgid "to create an XML file at ``path``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:484
msgid ""
"To set the name of the root test suite xml item, you can configure the "
"``junit_suite_name`` option in your config file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:486
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_suite_name = my_suite"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:493
msgid ""
"JUnit XML specification seems to indicate that ``\"time\"`` attribute should "
"report total test execution times, including setup and teardown (`1 <http://"
"windyroad.com.au/dl/Open%20Source/JUnit.xsd>`_, `2 <https://www.ibm.com/"
"support/knowledgecenter/en/SSQ2R2_14.1.0/com.ibm.rsar.analysis.codereview."
"cobol.doc/topics/cac_useresults_junit.html>`_). It is the default pytest "
"behavior. To report just call durations instead, configure the "
"``junit_duration_report`` option like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:500
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"junit_duration_report = call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:508
msgid "record_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:510
msgid ""
"If you want to log additional information for a test, you can use the "
"``record_property`` fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:513
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_property):\n"
"    record_property(\"example_key\", 1)\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:519
msgid ""
"This will add an extra property ``example_key=\"1\"`` to the generated "
"``testcase`` tag:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:522
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"example_key\" value=\"1\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:530
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can integrate this functionality with custom markers:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:532
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def pytest_collection_modifyitems(session, config, items):\n"
"    for item in items:\n"
"        for marker in item.iter_markers(name=\"test_id\"):\n"
"            test_id = marker.args[0]\n"
"            item.user_properties.append((\"test_id\", test_id))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:543
msgid "And in your tests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:545
msgid ""
"# content of test_function.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.test_id(1501)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:555
msgid "Will result in:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:557
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"test_function\" file=\"test_function.py\" line=\"0\" "
"name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.0009\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"test_id\" value=\"1501\" />\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:567 ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:632
msgid ""
"Please note that using this feature will break schema verifications for the "
"latest JUnitXML schema. This might be a problem when used with some CI "
"servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:571
msgid "record_xml_attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:575
msgid ""
"To add an additional xml attribute to a testcase element, you can use "
"``record_xml_attribute`` fixture. This can also be used to override existing "
"values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:578
msgid ""
"def test_function(record_xml_attribute):\n"
"    record_xml_attribute(\"assertions\", \"REQ-1234\")\n"
"    record_xml_attribute(\"classname\", \"custom_classname\")\n"
"    print(\"hello world\")\n"
"    assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:586
msgid ""
"Unlike ``record_property``, this will not add a new child element. Instead, "
"this will add an attribute ``assertions=\"REQ-1234\"`` inside the generated "
"``testcase`` tag and override the default ``classname`` with "
"``\"classname=custom_classname\"``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:590
msgid ""
"<testcase classname=\"custom_classname\" file=\"test_function.py\" "
"line=\"0\" name=\"test_function\" time=\"0.003\" assertions=\"REQ-1234\">\n"
"    <system-out>\n"
"        hello world\n"
"    </system-out>\n"
"</testcase>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:600
msgid ""
"``record_xml_attribute`` is an experimental feature, and its interface might "
"be replaced by something more powerful and general in future versions. The "
"functionality per-se will be kept, however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:604
msgid ""
"Using this over ``record_xml_property`` can help when using ci tools to "
"parse the xml report. However, some parsers are quite strict about the "
"elements and attributes that are allowed. Many tools use an xsd schema (like "
"the example below) to validate incoming xml. Make sure you are using "
"attribute names that are allowed by your parser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:609
msgid "Below is the Scheme used by Jenkins to validate the XML report:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:611
msgid ""
"<xs:element name=\"testcase\">\n"
"    <xs:complexType>\n"
"        <xs:sequence>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"skipped\" minOccurs=\"0\" maxOccurs=\"1\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"error\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"failure\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"system-out\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"            <xs:element ref=\"system-err\" minOccurs=\"0\" "
"maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"/>\n"
"        </xs:sequence>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"name\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"required\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"assertions\" type=\"xs:string\" "
"use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"time\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"classname\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/"
">\n"
"        <xs:attribute name=\"status\" type=\"xs:string\" use=\"optional\"/>\n"
"    </xs:complexType>\n"
"</xs:element>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:638
msgid "record_testsuite_property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:642
msgid ""
"If you want to add a properties node at the test-suite level, which may "
"contains properties that are relevant to all tests, you can use the "
"``record_testsuite_property`` session-scoped fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:645
msgid ""
"The ``record_testsuite_property`` session-scoped fixture can be used to add "
"properties relevant to all tests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:648
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(scope=\"session\", autouse=True)\n"
"def log_global_env_facts(record_testsuite_property):\n"
"    record_testsuite_property(\"ARCH\", \"PPC\")\n"
"    record_testsuite_property(\"STORAGE_TYPE\", \"CEPH\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class TestMe:\n"
"    def test_foo(self):\n"
"        assert True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:663
msgid ""
"The fixture is a callable which receives ``name`` and ``value`` of a "
"``<property>`` tag added at the test-suite level of the generated xml:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:666
msgid ""
"<testsuite errors=\"0\" failures=\"0\" name=\"pytest\" skipped=\"0\" "
"tests=\"1\" time=\"0.006\">\n"
"  <properties>\n"
"    <property name=\"ARCH\" value=\"PPC\"/>\n"
"    <property name=\"STORAGE_TYPE\" value=\"CEPH\"/>\n"
"  </properties>\n"
"  <testcase classname=\"test_me.TestMe\" file=\"test_me.py\" line=\"16\" "
"name=\"test_foo\" time=\"0.000243663787842\"/>\n"
"</testsuite>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:676
msgid ""
"``name`` must be a string, ``value`` will be converted to a string and "
"properly xml-escaped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:678
msgid ""
"The generated XML is compatible with the latest ``xunit`` standard, contrary "
"to `record_property`_ and `record_xml_attribute`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:683
msgid "Creating resultlog format files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:686
msgid "To create plain-text machine-readable result files you can issue:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:688
msgid "pytest --resultlog=path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:692
msgid ""
"and look at the content at the ``path`` location.  Such files are used e.g. "
"by the `PyPy-test`_ web page to show test results over several revisions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:697
msgid "This option is rarely used and is scheduled for removal in pytest 6.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:699
msgid ""
"If you use this option, consider using the new `pytest-reportlog <https://"
"github.com/pytest-dev/pytest-reportlog>`__ plugin instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:701
msgid ""
"See `the deprecation docs <https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/deprecations."
"html#result-log-result-log>`__ for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:709
msgid "Sending test report to online pastebin service"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:711
msgid "**Creating a URL for each test failure**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:713
msgid "pytest --pastebin=failed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:717
msgid ""
"This will submit test run information to a remote Paste service and provide "
"a URL for each failure.  You may select tests as usual or add for example ``-"
"x`` if you only want to send one particular failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:721
msgid "**Creating a URL for a whole test session log**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:723
msgid "pytest --pastebin=all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:727
msgid "Currently only pasting to the http://bpaste.net service is implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:731
msgid ""
"If creating the URL fails for any reason, a warning is generated instead of "
"failing the entire test suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:735
msgid "Early loading plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:737
msgid ""
"You can early-load plugins (internal and external) explicitly in the command-"
"line with the ``-p`` option::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:739
msgid "pytest -p mypluginmodule"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:741
msgid "The option receives a ``name`` parameter, which can be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:743
msgid ""
"A full module dotted name, for example ``myproject.plugins``. This dotted "
"name must be importable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:744
msgid ""
"The entry-point name of a plugin. This is the name passed to ``setuptools`` "
"when the plugin is registered. For example to early-load the `pytest-cov "
"<https://pypi.org/project/pytest-cov/>`__ plugin you can use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:747
msgid "pytest -p pytest_cov"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:751
msgid "Disabling plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:753
msgid ""
"To disable loading specific plugins at invocation time, use the ``-p`` "
"option together with the prefix ``no:``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:756
msgid ""
"Example: to disable loading the plugin ``doctest``, which is responsible for "
"executing doctest tests from text files, invoke pytest like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:759
msgid "pytest -p no:doctest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:766
msgid "Calling pytest from Python code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:770
msgid "You can invoke ``pytest`` from Python code directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:772
msgid "pytest.main()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:776
msgid ""
"this acts as if you would call \"pytest\" from the command line. It will not "
"raise ``SystemExit`` but return the exitcode instead. You can pass in "
"options and arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:780
msgid "pytest.main([\"-x\", \"mytestdir\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:784
msgid "You can specify additional plugins to ``pytest.main``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:786
msgid ""
"# content of myinvoke.py\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPlugin:\n"
"    def pytest_sessionfinish(self):\n"
"        print(\"*** test run reporting finishing\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"pytest.main([\"-qq\"], plugins=[MyPlugin()])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:799
msgid ""
"Running it will show that ``MyPlugin`` was added and its hook was invoked:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:802
msgid ""
"$ python myinvoke.py\n"
".FEsxX.                                                              "
"[100%]*** test run reporting finishing\n"
"\n"
"================================== ERRORS "
"==================================\n"
"_______________________ ERROR at setup of test_error "
"_______________________\n"
"\n"
"    @pytest.fixture\n"
"    def error_fixture():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:6: AssertionError\n"
"================================= FAILURES "
"=================================\n"
"________________________________ test_fail "
"_________________________________\n"
"\n"
"    def test_fail():\n"
">       assert 0\n"
"E       assert 0\n"
"\n"
"test_example.py:14: AssertionError\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"FAILED test_example.py::test_fail - assert 0\n"
"ERROR test_example.py::test_error - assert 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/usage.rst:830
msgid ""
"Calling ``pytest.main()`` will result in importing your tests and any "
"modules that they import. Due to the caching mechanism of python's import "
"system, making subsequent calls to ``pytest.main()`` from the same process "
"will not reflect changes to those files between the calls. For this reason, "
"making multiple calls to ``pytest.main()`` from the same process (in order "
"to re-run tests, for example) is not recommended."
msgstr ""
